    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 282,
    "last_activity_date" : 1654174670,
    "last_edit_date" : 1654174670,
    "creation_date" : 1266335532,
    "answer_id" : 2274130,
    "question_id" : 2274102,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The first one catches all subclasses of <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Throwable.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Throwable</code></a> (this includes <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Exception.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Exception</code></a> and <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Error.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Error</code></a>), the second one catches all subclasses of <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Exception.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Exception</code></a>.</p>\n<p><code>Error</code> is programmatically unrecoverable in any way and is usually not to be caught, except for logging purposes (which passes it through again). <code>Exception</code> is programmatically recoverable. Its subclass <code>RuntimeException</code> indicates a programming error and is usually not to be caught as well.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 85022,
      "reputation" : 14131,
      "user_id" : 237321,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1c7d2d36a86da481db7d5db58bf3109c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "x4u",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/237321/x4u"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 41,
    "last_activity_date" : 1637752477,
    "last_edit_date" : 1637752477,
    "creation_date" : 1266335812,
    "answer_id" : 2274166,
    "question_id" : 2274102,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Throwable</code> catches really everything even ThreadDeath which gets thrown by default to stop a thread from the now deprecated <code>Thread.stop()</code> method. So by catching <code>Throwable</code> you can be sure that you'll never leave the try block without at least going through your catch block, but you should be prepared to also handle <code>OutOfMemoryError</code> and <code>InternalError</code> or <code>StackOverflowError</code>.</p>\n<p>Catching <code>Throwable</code> is most useful for outer server loops that delegate all sorts of requests to outside code but may itself never terminate to keep the service alive.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1923293,
      "reputation" : 10705,
      "user_id" : 1734279,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/6VA46.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "rai.skumar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1734279/rai-skumar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 45,
    "last_activity_date" : 1518154236,
    "last_edit_date" : 1518154236,
    "creation_date" : 1407219892,
    "answer_id" : 25132383,
    "question_id" : 2274102,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Throwable</code> is super class of <code>Exception</code> as well as <code>Error</code>. In normal cases we should always catch sub-classes of <code>Exception</code>, so that the root cause doesn't get lost. </p>\n\n<p>Only special cases where you see possibility of things going wrong which is not in control of your Java code, you should catch <code>Error</code> or <code>Throwable</code>. </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>I remember catching Throwable to flag that a native library is not loaded. </p>\n</blockquote>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 419243,
      "reputation" : 585,
      "user_id" : 796295,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/46728882732ef30a61b6689e3cd79f63?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Spear A1",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/796295/spear-a1"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1573163271,
    "creation_date" : 1573163271,
    "answer_id" : 58757375,
    "question_id" : 2274102,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I have seen people use Throwable to catch some errors that might happen due to infra failure/ non availability. </p>\n"
